# Mock Fidelity

> **"A test that passes against a wrong-signature mock is a test that didn't run."**

This rule was written after a real bug: a `jest.mock` for `ApiError` declared
`constructor(status: number, message: string)` and the test called
`new ApiError(400, "Failed to parse reference")`. The real class is
`constructor(status, body: ApiErrorBody)` where `body` is `{code, message, ...}`.
Tests that "asserted error handling" were silently asserting against a fake
shape. CI never caught it because every test was internally consistent. A
human reviewer (Emmet) caught it on push.

## Two Forbidden Moves

### 1. Invented Mock Signatures

Before mocking ANY symbol from production code, you MUST read the real
declaration. The mock's public surface (constructor args, method
signatures, exported field names and types) MUST match the real one.

| Wrong | Right |
| --- | --- |
| Skim the test that uses the mock and infer the shape | Open the production module and read the declaration |
| "It's just a stub, the shape doesn't matter" | The shape IS the contract — drift here means tests prove nothing |
| Use `any` to make the mock "flexible" | Mirror the real types so type-checking catches signature changes |

If the real class's signature changes, the mock should fail to type-check.
That's the safety net. `any` silently disables it.

### 2. Silencing Linters to Work Around Jest Hoisting

`jest.mock(...)` calls are hoisted by Jest's transform to the very top of
the file, BEFORE imports. So this works:

```typescript
// jest.mock factory runs first (hoisted), then imports resolve to the mocked module.
jest.mock("@/lib/api-client", () => ({ ApiError: class extends Error {} }));
import { ApiError } from "@/lib/api-client";  // <-- resolves to the mock
```

If you find yourself reaching for ANY of these patterns, stop:

| Anti-pattern | Why it's wrong |
| --- | --- |
| `const { X } = require("@/lib/...")` after `jest.mock(...)` | Hoisting already handled it — `require` is dead weight |
| `// eslint-disable-next-line @typescript-eslint/no-require-imports` | You're silencing the rule that exists to catch this exact thing |
| `// @ts-ignore` on a mocked import | Type the mock correctly; ts-ignore hides the real bug |
| Defining the mock class OUTSIDE the `jest.mock` factory | Triggers "Cannot access 'X' before initialization" — solve by moving the class INSIDE the factory, not by `require`-ing it back out |

The fix is always: define the mock class inside the `jest.mock` factory,
then use a top-level `import { X as MockedX } from "@/lib/..."` to get a
typed reference. No `require`, no `eslint-disable`.

## The Reading Protocol (For Mocks)

Before writing any new `jest.mock(...)` factory:

1. Open the production module being mocked
2. Read every export the test will reach for
3. Copy the constructor / function signatures into the mock
4. If the production type uses an interface (`ApiErrorBody`), reference it
   in the mock so a future field addition forces a test update

## When a Test Catches Less Than It Claims

If a test name says "handles ApiError 400 correctly" but the mock's
`ApiError` doesn't accept the same constructor args as the real class,
the test does NOT verify production behaviour. Fix the mock first, then
verify the test still passes — and if it doesn't, you've found a real
bug the wrong mock was hiding.

## Anti-Patterns

| Anti-Pattern | Consequence |
| --- | --- |
| Mocks shaped from how the test reads | Tests pass with wrong-signature production code |
| `any` in mocks | Signature changes don't break the test |
| `eslint-disable` for hoisting | The next reader copy-pastes the workaround |
| Adding `// @ts-ignore` to mocked imports | Real type errors hidden |

> **"Mocks are part of the contract. Treat them with the same rigor as the production type."**
